body:
#### Summary

When using ignoringAllOverriddenEquals with lenient type comparison e.g. DTO, if a field on actual is an `enum` and the field on expected with the same name is a `String`, then that field is silently ignored.
Using a custom comparator for the field solves this but it's not obvious that it's required so can easily be missed currently.
https://assertj.github.io/doc/#assertj-core-recursive-comparison-ignoring-equals

The reverse scenario works fine and reports `expected field is an enum but actual field is not (java.lang.String)` rather than ignoring the field when there is no custom comparator.

Using a debugger I've found that in RecursiveComparisonConfiguration,
```java
Set<String> getNonIgnoredActualFieldNames(DualValue dualValue) {
  Set<String> actualFieldsNames = Objects.getFieldsNames(dualValue.actual.getClass());
```  
  doesn't find any `actualFieldsNames` when `dualValue` actual is an `enum` e.g. PersonDTO.JobTitle
  so the field `jobTitle` is ignored when comparing the fields.

#### Example

```java
public class BlogPost {
    Person author;
}
public class BlogPostDTO {
    PersonDTO author;
}
public class Person {
    String name;
    String jobTitle;
}
public class PersonDTO {
    String name;
    JobTitle jobTitle;

    public enum JobTitle {
        SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER,
        QA_ENGINEER
    }
}

Person devPerson = Person.builder().name("Example Name").jobTitle("SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER").build();
BlogPost devBlogPost = BlogPost.builder().author(devPerson).build();
PersonDTO devPersonDTO = PersonDTO.builder().name("Example Name").jobTitle(PersonDTO.JobTitle.SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER).build();
BlogPostDTO devBlogPostDTO = BlogPostDTO.builder().author(devPersonDTO).build();
Person qaPerson = Person.builder().name("Example Name").jobTitle("QA_ENGINEER").build();
BlogPost qaBlogPost = BlogPost.builder().author(qaPerson).build();
PersonDTO qaPersonDTO = PersonDTO.builder().name("Example Name").jobTitle(PersonDTO.JobTitle.QA_ENGINEER).build();
BlogPostDTO qaBlogPostDTO = BlogPostDTO.builder().author(qaPersonDTO).build();

// This is expected to fail but passes
// qaBlogPost should not be equal to devBlogPostDTO but the jobTitle field appears to be ignored when there is no custom comparator
// Expected behaviour (based on the reverse direction existing behaviour):
// - failure due to not being able to compare an enum with a string for author.jobTitle
assertThat(devBlogPostDTO)
    .usingRecursiveComparison()
    .ignoringAllOverriddenEquals()
    .isEqualTo(qaBlogPost);

// This is expected to pass and does but it's odd that isEqualTo and isNotEqualTo both pass when comparing the same two objects
assertThat(devBlogPostDTO)
    .usingRecursiveComparison()
    .ignoringAllOverriddenEquals()
    .isNotEqualTo(qaBlogPost);

 // Using a custom comparator avoids the issue
assertThat(devBlogPostDTO)
    .usingRecursiveComparison()
    .ignoringAllOverriddenEquals()
    .withComparatorForFields((enumJobTitle, stringJobTitle) ->
            (stringJobTitle == null && enumJobTitle == null)
                || (stringJobTitle != null
                && enumJobTitle != null
                && stringJobTitle.equals(((PersonDTO.JobTitle) enumJobTitle).name())) ? 0 : 1,
        "author.jobTitle"
    )
    .isNotEqualTo(qaBlogPost);

// The reverse works OK already (this fails as expected with the output pasted below)
assertThat(devBlogPost)
    .usingRecursiveComparison()
    .ignoringAllOverriddenEquals()
    .isEqualTo(devBlogPostDTO);
```
```
Output:
java.lang.AssertionError: 
Expecting:
  <BlogPost(author=Person(name=Example Name, jobTitle=SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER))>
to be equal to:
  <BlogPostDTO(author=PersonDTO(name=Example Name, jobTitle=SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER))>
when recursively comparing field by field, but found the following difference:

field/property 'author.jobTitle' differ:
- actual value   : "SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER"
- expected value : SOFTWARE_DEVELOPER
expected field is an enum but actual field is not (java.lang.String)
```
